While I agree with this commit, the change would result in a clearer API error, this doesn't exactly fix a bug, it just changes the http response from 500 to 409, so it changes from one error to another, so it isn't really compatible with the backport policy.

According to the Stable Branch Policy, API changes are forbidden, although the change was/is compatible with the master branch API change policy.

Also, Icehouse is in Phase II Support, meaning only critical bugfixes and security bug fixes are acceptable and I don't think this fits any of the categories.

Also, marking as WIP, since it didn't merge in Juno yet.

commit_message:
Correctly catch InstanceExists in servers create API

When osapi_compute_unique_server_name_scope is set to project
or global an attempt to create a server with a name which
already exists results in an InstanceExists exception being raised.
This was not being handled in the API layer causing a 500
status error code. This patch fixes it so the exception is caught
correctly and a 409 Conflict is returned instead

Closes-Bug: 1376936
Closes-Bug: 1377176
(cherry picked from commit 8cedf63e5ccc9a023884b77fc460f8372300012d)

Change-Id: Ifee3476622b227991a4c2a2780ae7ff23787ccb9

commit_message:
Add ability to add mongo nodes to operational environment

  During first run we are logging into mongo without authentication
  and can successfully add nodes. Users will be created later.
  On second (and all next) deployment run, when we are trying to add
  new mongo nodes, we should use admin credentials to evaluate these commands

  Closes-bug: #1308990

Change-Id: I1addc251f92b931dbea6800ca86e7d65e8e0e033

commit_message:
Set Rabbit recovery method for network partitions

Adds configurable option rabbit_cluster_partition_handling with default
value of pause_minority. Allows option to be explicitly set to ignore
through Ansible to reset to prior (and RabbitMQ default) behavior.

Change-Id: I4a2cf86bd08de70ac42e417a3fbbac550f4d464f
Closes-Bug: #1454860

Please see my inline in detail.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-05-11 13:32:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(8 comments)

@Kota I'm still torn over introducing the new subreq simply because the interaction of these requests and subrequests has sometimes hidden subtle bugs, and because there is a comment in COPY that explicitly say not to make a new request (something to do with posthooklogger but I cannot figure out what that refers to). I do understand your point though.

-1 for the moment simply because the new functional tests cause another to fail on my SAIO running with post_as_copy = false [1]. Thats not your fault, its a bug [2] + test coupling, but I'd like not to merge failing tests ;) 

The failure is caused by your tests making a POST request to a manifest that is used in the failing test. My suggestion would be to work around the bug by creating fresh manifests for your functional tests so there is no coupling with the other test.

[1] http://paste.openstack.org/show/219852/
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/swift/+bug/1453807"}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2015-05-12 05:12:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(5 comments)

@Alistair

Thanks for reviewing so deeply, I didn't notice the fast-post bug, nice catch!

For now, I'm realizing we have to discuss whether we should use sub_req in another place because, imo, we should work around posthook. (maybe we should get rid of the posthook constraint because it seems older one before proxy_logging middleware was built. Older Swift seems to use eventlet.post_hook for logging)

I'll try both to remove the sub_req implementation and to make the functional test to avoid the fast post bug on the next patch."}, {'account_id': 4608, 'date': '2015-05-12 06:08:52.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-12 06:53:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

Reply your inline comments.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-30 04:52:08.000000000', 'message': 'Remove confusable query string on post as copy

Current post as copy routine (i.e. POST object with post_as_copy option
turned on) on Object Controller uses "multipart-manifest" query string
which is feeded to env['copy_hook'] to decide which data (the manifest or
object pointed by the manifest) should be copied.

However, the way using the query string will confuse operators looking at
logging system (or analyzing the log) because whole POST object requests
have 'multipart-manifest=get' like as:

POST /v1/AUTH_test/d4c816b24d38489082f5118599a67920/manifest-abcde%3Fmultipart-manifest%3Dget

We cannot know whether the query string was added by hand
(from user) or not. In addition, the query isn't needed by the
backend conversation between proxy-server and object-server.
(Just needed by "copy_hook" on the proxy controller!)

To remove the confusable query string and to keep the log to be clean,
this patch introduces new environment variable "swift.post_as_copy"
and changes proxy controller and the copy_hook to use the new env.

This item was originally discussed at
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177132/

Change-Id: I0cd37520eea1825a10ebd27ccdc7e9162647233e

commit_message:
Remove confusable query string on post as copy

Current post as copy routine (i.e. POST object with post_as_copy option
turned on) on Object Controller uses "multipart-manifest" query string
which is feeded to env['copy_hook'] to decide which data (the manifest or
object pointed by the manifest) should be copied.

However, the way using the query string will confuse operators looking at
logging system (or analyzing the log) because whole POST object requests
have 'multipart-manifest=get' like as:

POST /v1/AUTH_test/d4c816b24d38489082f5118599a67920/manifest-abcde%3Fmultipart-manifest%3Dget

We cannot know whether the query string was added by hand
(from user) or not. In addition, the query isn't needed by the
backend conversation between proxy-server and object-server.
(Just needed by "copy_hook" on the proxy controller!)

To remove the confusable query string and to keep the log to be clean,
this patch introduces new environment variable "swift.post_as_copy"
and changes proxy controller and the copy_hook to use the new env.

This item was originally discussed at
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/177132/

Co-Authored-By: Alistair Coles <alistair.coles@hp.com>

Change-Id: I0cd37520eea1825a10ebd27ccdc7e9162647233e

commit_message:
Remove blazar from projects.txt

The blazar project contains now lockfile which has been removed from
global requirements and thus the propose-requirements change for blazar
fails, see
https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/propose-requirements-updates/35/consoleFull
Error message is:
'lockfile' is not in global-requirements.txt

Remove blazar from the list since the project is inactive, last merge
was August 2014.

Change-Id: I3571c3d67d909083929c4b9b8be3f9d754d20da9

I also wanted to talk to ericwb about https://review.openstack.org/#/c/180326/ and see if that is necessary for this change."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-05-28 14:12:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

It's still not clear what is the bug to be fixed by the backport. The fact that there is a Launchpad bug created does not mean there is actually a bug in the product.

It looks like the patch enables support for some (advanced?) network scheme in VMWare. Should we consider it a feature that are not allowed usually in the stable tree?

The patch itself looks innocent though. At the same time, if glance patch mentioned by Matt is indeed needed, then it complicates the matter a bit since glance patch touches files inside /etc/ that are usually considered config files not to be replaced automatically. Meaning, there would be an additional upgrade action to apply for operators on minor update. Is it acceptable? Will the old glance .json file still work for other users that do not rely on that new networking scheme?

Clarifications are needed."}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2015-05-28 15:13:54.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

[{'created': '2015-05-26 20:40:02.000000000', 'message': 'Sort _get_remote_sg_ids, _determine_remote_sgs_to_remove in unittests

This fixes the iptables_firewall group unit tests[1] that breaks with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that the _get_remote_sg_ids and
_determine_remote_sgs_to_remove methods from
neutron.agent.linux.iptables_firewall returned elements in a particular
order. Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=1.

The fix refactors the test case to force lexigraphic-ordered (dict)
responses.

[1] neutron.tests.unit.agent.linux.test_iptables_firewall:
 test_prepare_port_filter_with_new_members
 test_prepare_port_filter_with_sg_no_member
 test_remove_port_filter_with_destroy_ipset_chain

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: I19e51452a2bde0721559df746047239f68614336

commit_message:
Do not assume order of iptables_firewall method responses

This fixes the iptables_firewall group unit tests[1] that breaks with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that the _get_remote_sg_ids and
_determine_remote_sgs_to_remove methods from
neutron.agent.linux.iptables_firewall returned elements in a particular
order. Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=1.

The fix refactors the test case to handle unsorted responses from
_get_remote_sg_ids and _determine_remote_sgs_to_remove.

[1] neutron.tests.unit.agent.linux.test_iptables_firewall:
 test_prepare_port_filter_with_new_members
 test_prepare_port_filter_with_sg_no_member
 test_remove_port_filter_with_destroy_ipset_chain

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: I19e51452a2bde0721559df746047239f68614336

commit_message:
Create a wrapper to apache start and stop

Stop/Start apache service, on failure repeat operation after timeout

Closes-bug: #1457893
Related-Bug: #1459357
Change-Id: I906139554c7cf770ffdac29f95d3d97f29b87f43
Signed-off-by: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovatiuk@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Drop incubating theme from docs

OpenStack has dropped the incubation notion, so labeling this as an
incubated project in the docs is confusing.

Change-Id: I1cdcecc4974ab248cae1a9cccdb587e7256cc993

commit_message:
qpid: Always auto-delete queue of DirectConsumer

In case of the call()er die, the queue used to reply must be
automatically deleted, otherwise they will never been deleted.

This is done in the same way as the rabbit drivers does,
by enabling auto-delete on this queue.

Change-Id: Ib01981d704b8849e0115791ff90fbb74cbac421f
Closes-Bug: #1374519
(cherry picked from commit 1640cc17031bde765d7e272c2e65993c4b270a45)

commit_message:
Add process name checking into swift-init

Swift-init uses pid files to detect existing swift processes by pid.
However, it mistakes an unrelated process for a swift process and makes
a wrong decision, when the unrelated process is running with pid written
in swift pid files.
This patch adds process name checking into swift-init and enable it to remove
invalid pid files in such situation.

Change-Id: Ibca026bdfbdacdd92c8763e1eb15d98293c70656
Closes-Bug: #1327106

commit_message:
Add set_one_cloud method

It is useful for clients to be able to update configuration as well.
By doing this in shade we can perform things like merging and do some
testing rather than require clients to do it.

Change-Id: Ia185847c29c10f2cc6838adf962defd80894d0db

commit_message:
More caps based on dsvm-full and dsvm-neutron pip-freeze.txt

qpid-python version cap is raised till <=0.26 since DEB package we
install from distribution repository is lower than the minimal version
available from PyPI (which is 0.20 at the moment).

Pip freeze output is taken from:
http://logs.openstack.org/62/171562/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full/4bd4896/
http://logs.openstack.org/62/171562/1/check/check-tempest-dsvm-neutron/833c3da/

Change-Id: I325a8646f5f13f83735de59cede5d5f7f2973a1d

commit_message:
fix net-create call for public1 in tools/init-runonce

The --router:external option is a boolean flag that doesn't take a value
(neutron client version 2.5.0). Passing True results in the following
error:

Invalid values_specs True

This patch simply removes the 'True' value.

Change-Id: If4b5305f37d50c14c767393eb21223b0e0b59494
(cherry picked from commit 4443392f6e7315328880a2744cd89492045d8507)

commit_message:
Fix issue with configuring HDP cluster

When node groups of cluster have uppercase letters in name,
cluster can't be configured. This patch resolve this issue, because
there is no sense in making node group name lowercase during creating
Clusterspec object.

Change-Id: I6ada7468bc1a6826727d330730cdc57c789f70b7
Closes-bug: 1263722

commit_message:
Add flag to indicate handling of security groups

Security groups can be handled by either nova, neutron, or just
not be supported. This adds a flag for that. Values will be one
of 'neutron' (the default), 'nova', or None. None indicates that
security groups are not supported.

Change-Id: I81a2e10e14e53acc9ffc328771d8ef721e2fd370

commit_message:
Don't normalize too deeply

We were normalizing the entire clouds.yaml output - but the keys
underneath clouds: are names of clouds. We should not touch them.

Instead - normalize the keys of the config dict we return.

Change-Id: I792475d701d31201a9be6d54e066227d97b7ce5f

commit_message:
Remove simplejson from swift-recon

Since we're dropping Python 2.6 support, we can rely on stdlib's json
and get rid of our dependency on simplejson.

All swift-recon was doing with json was decoding a JSON response (from
the recon middleware) and printing it to the terminal. This still
works just fine.

Change-Id: I28cf25a7c2856f230d4642c62fb8bf9c4d37e9e5

commit_message:
Don't fail on converting user ids to bytes

When building Fernet token payloads, we should attempt to convert user IDs to bytes
because this makes the payload a little smaller, resulting in a smaller token.
But if we are unable to convert the user ID to bytes we shouldn't fail with a
ValueError because the user ID could be coming from LDAP, or some other
external identity backend. We can't assume the user ID is a UUID.

Change-Id: I05b1e8389b15475c3fe512a2f82ec86f81422a05
Closes-Bug: 1459382

commit_message:
VPNaaS: Cleanup functional hook scripts

This does a few minor fixes. First, it changes the bash invocation
line. Next, it uses a case statement for one multicondition if-clause.
Third, it uses VENV for the virtual environemnt variable to be
consistent with gate_hook.sh.

Change-Id: I788c95657fe70e894bb55beca190ba6bedf71aca

commit_message:
Enable exception raising when OVSDB transaction fails

By default the OVSDB implementation suppresses exceptions raised in case
of OVSDB failures. This patch enables exception raising in order
to avoid introducing inconsistencies between Neutron DB and OVN NB DB.

Change-Id: Ifb138ee26b08f775f11f9b743977c250d8adb9af
Closes-Bug: #1443018

commit_message:
Sync service from oslo-incubator

Sync change [1] that had been reverted at the time of the previous
sync [2] due to bug 1438321.

Change log:
f5646ed Revert "Revert "Optimization of waiting subprocesses in ProcessLauncher""

Also, as monkey patching is done in parent process, os.waitpid(0, 0)
in _wait_child method also gets monkey-patched and eventlet goes crazy.
Connecting to parent process with strace shows that os.waitpid(0, os.WNOHANG)
is called, yet it is difficult to say what is really happening because
the process does not react on termination signals (SIGTERM, SIGHUP, SIGINT).

The solution is not to monkey patch os.waitpid, that is why in this change
the original os.waitpid is preserved.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/156345/
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/167974/

Change-Id: I50378baff36aadedcc36aafc4faf09590eaa16b9
Closes-Bug: #1438321

commit_message:
Updating Case Studies - Alice's Instance Security Management section

+ Clarifying additional consideration before hardware is selected of
  rdrand support highlighted in RFP
+ Using egd + libvirt
+ Using 'trusted compute pools' for attestation
+ Ensuring logging captures on-system commands in images
+ HIDS agent is used
+ Calls out architectural dependency that requires clear ownership
+ Moved comma up and used <filname> tag

Change-Id: I8861bb8c1dace8fc7526a1464c6abc61faac032e
Partial-Bug: #1349540

[{'created': '2015-04-27 07:13:39.000000000', 'message': "Eventlet green threads not released back to pool

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections hence even after
the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket
connection.
Because of this problem, the green thread is not released back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

Add a parameter to take advantage of the new(ish) eventlet socket timeout
behaviour. Allows closing idle client connections after a period of
time, eg:

$ time nc localhost 8776
real    1m0.063s

Setting 'client_socket_timeout = 0' means do not timeout.

DocImpact:
Added wsgi_keep_alive option (default=True).
Added client_socket_timeout option (default=900).

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1361360
Change-Id: I03b9c5c64f4bd8bca78dfc83199ef17d9a7ea5b7
(cherry picked from commit 3b08644eb9cf4c5aca51a36250ae93105c17f6c4)
"}]
commit_message:
Eventlet green threads not released back to pool

Presently, the wsgi server allows persist connections hence even after
the response is sent to the client, it doesn't close the client socket
connection.
Because of this problem, the green thread is not released back to the pool.

In order to close the client socket connection explicitly after the
response is sent and read successfully by the client, you simply have to
set keepalive to False when you create a wsgi server.

Add a parameter to take advantage of the new(ish) eventlet socket timeout
behaviour. Allows closing idle client connections after a period of
time, eg:

$ time nc localhost 8776
real    1m0.063s

Setting 'client_socket_timeout = 0' means do not timeout.

DocImpact:
Added wsgi_keep_alive option (default=True).
Added client_socket_timeout option (default=900).

SecurityImpact

Closes-Bug: #1361360
Change-Id: I03b9c5c64f4bd8bca78dfc83199ef17d9a7ea5b7
(cherry picked from commit 3b08644eb9cf4c5aca51a36250ae93105c17f6c4)

commit_message:
Support conditions for bonding modes

'broadcast', 'balance-xor', 'balance-alb', 'balance-tlb'
linux bond modes will be accessible from UI in experimental mode only.

This will also undo https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186088/ changes.

Change-Id: I87bc7275277a77acf6a256dcfe93516c5d684cc9
Related-Bug: #1458935

commit_message:
[upstream-training] remove Makefile

The available and documented tox virutal environments should
be used to build the upstream training guide and not the Makefile. To
avoid confusion the Makefile should be removed.

Change-Id: I65cd0ddb307f02909062c1129cddfa651eeaa2ba

commit_message:
Add an index to virtual_interfaces.uuid

Performance issues have been reported such
that the query performed by virtual_interface_get_by_uuid
becomes prohibitively slow after a large (~250K) number of instances
have been created, and an attempt is made to launch instances
in batch.  An index added to uuid shows a dramatic improvement
to this query in EXPLAIN testing.

Cherry-picked from: d65bb6de033deaa5f7cf88bca364fc80cf0b2f75

Change-Id: I0bac6f21c5b52ca6691e23b8a0dc68f001d14c18

commit_message:
Do not assume order of convert_kvp_list_to_dict method responses

This fixes the test_attributes unit tests[1] that breaks with a
randomized PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that the convert_kvp_list_to_dict method from
neutron.api.v2.attributes returned elements in a particular
order. Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=1.

The fix refactors the test case to handle unsorted responses from
convert_kvp_list_to_dict.

[1] neutron.tests.unit.api.v2.test_attributes.TestConvertKvp

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: I864904db1428b88c482ad17a69b33e876a8d042c

commit_message:
Updating Case Studies - Alice's Monitoring & Logging

Updating Alice's Monitoring & Logging:
+ SOC analyst to monitor events
+ SEIM already exists
+ Ensures rest of SOC doesn't have access
+ Service groups get own views
+ Clarity around SOC analyst and trimming whitespace

One gap is specific events. As soon as this is merged, I will open a
bug against specific log types being tracked and will highlight what
events Alice is looking for each component, however I expect the
research on that to take some time and this should be put up in the
mean time.

Change-Id: I42e5b6e214025cda309a525bff5f8a805d33b664
Partial-Bug: #1349540

commit_message:
Templatize zuul: Use python*-jobs

Use python3-jobs and python-jobs templates instead of spelling out the
jobs. This converts all python34 occurences in both check and gate, and
one python-jobs that I noticed.

[{'created': '2015-05-27 21:57:30.000000000', 'message': 'Remove time formatting in agent clock error

This removes time formatting that may be hiding timezone
issues that are leading to a delta being calculated between
the agent and the server even when it shows none. It also
adds logging of the difference so we can see how far off it
thinks they are.

Example message:
during the registration of Open vSwitch agent has a timestamp:
2015-05-19T18:15:27Z. This differs from the current server
timestamp: 2015-05-19T18:15:27Z by more than the threshold agent

Note that the timestamps are exactly the same after formatting.

Related-Bug: #1456760
'}]
commit_message:
Remove time formatting in agent clock error

This removes time formatting that may be hiding timezone
issues that are leading to a delta being calculated between
the agent and the server even when it shows none. It also
adds logging of the difference so we can see how far off it
thinks they are.

Example message:
during the registration of Open vSwitch agent has a timestamp:
2015-05-19T18:15:27Z. This differs from the current server
timestamp: 2015-05-19T18:15:27Z by more than the threshold agent
downtime: 75.

Note that the timestamps are exactly the same after formatting.

Change-Id: Ibfc30444b7a167fb18ae9051a775266236d4ecce
Related-Bug: #1456760

commit_message:
Fix Python 3 issues

* Replace it.next() with next(it)
* Replace dict.iteritems() with six.iteritems(dict)
* Replace unicode with six.text_type
* Replace dict(d1.items() + {'Cookie': cookie}.items()) with:
  d3=dict(d1); d3['Cookie'] = cookie
* Replace map(func, parts) with [func(part) for part in parts]
* Open file in binary mode (not in text mode) to load JSON using
  jsonutils.load()
* Avoid using dict.keys()[0] or dict.values()[0]: on Python 3, keys()
  and values() methods of dictionaries return iterators, not lists

For more information on Python 3, see:
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3

Change-Id: Ib09a3367d8dcb664911a0b187da9e363a96727fd

commit_message:
Support mgmt network creation

PowerVM systems use a technology called Resource Monitoring and Control
(RMC).  This allows the hypervisor to perform dynamic operations to the
virtual machine (resize, migration, etc...).

This technology requires an Ethernet connection between the VM and the
PowerVM API.  This change set enables this via two means.

 - Refactoring the existing 'mgmt' nic connection into tasks.  This
   enables further tasks to determine if a mgmt VIF was created.
 - Send an additional network info element into the config drive to
   bring up the VIF on IPv6 link local.

Change-Id: I11881203d753061d7a2127fd2a939462f69d39e7

commit_message:
Move SQL backends to requirements

New version of SQLAlchemy-utils require that we do install all the
backends we support otherwise it fails at runtime.

Change-Id: I8767fdf26f6278eb2f1ef4a483e8dcae7be43a2b

PEP-0247 introduced dict comprehensions [1], these are benefits:
  The dictionary constructor approach has two distinct disadvantages
  from the proposed syntax though.  First, it isn't as legible as a
  dict comprehension.  Second, it forces the programmer to create an
  in-core list object first, which could be expensive.

Cinder dropped python 2.6 support in Kilo, we can leaverage this now.

[1]http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0274/

commit_message:
Leverage dict comprehension in PEP-0274

PEP-0274 introduced dict comprehensions to replace dict constructor
with a sqeuence of key-pairs[1], these are benefits:
  First, it makes the code look neater.
  Second, it gains a micro-optimization.

Cinder dropped python 2.6 support in Kilo, we can leverage this now.
Note: This commit doesn't handle dict constructor with kwargs.
This commit also adds a hacking rule.

[1]http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0274/

Change-Id: Ie65796438160b1aa1f47c8519fb9943e81bff3e9

This is an interesting one, because I think its a bug in Neutron. I'm not sure on protocol here - at the very least we *definitely* need a TODO to remove these messages once the Neutron bug is fixed. I think a safer method would be to prevent deletion of a subnet if it is attached to a loadbalancer, since it is already a required field for loadbalancer creation. commit_message:
Throw a warning message when failed to get pool detail

When subnet associated to a pool deleted, the pool detail page will
throw an exception. Fix the problem by showing a warning message
when failed to get the expand resources for the pool.

Change-Id: I9f853505db625527de69c8f620b988e6e42a4339
Closes-bug: #1406879

commit_message:
Add a keystone-cinder-api constraint

Make sure the keystone service starts before the cinder-api one.

Change-Id: I21549c066afcf051e52fc4bba4fae2f34ad2ba4b

commit_message:
Add has_share_server param to share_type

Add new command-line param '--has-share-server' to 'type-create'
function. This option would be passed as optional extra-spec to
manila scheduler. Valid values: 'true'/'1' and 'false'/'0'.

Change-Id: I8fd428b59c588a59758095c5cbf542586e5b85f2

commit_message:
Change logic of get networks in attach_to_networks

In attach_to_networks method replace get_networks method to
   get_network and loop. This behavior save order of nets
   which setted via system environment.

Change-Id: I2186acbae44aa64dab311bd1224e1c7540547a63
Closes-bug: #1456288
Closes-bug: #1444058
Closes-bug: #1454786

commit_message:
Don't catch rbd import errors

Since now drivers are opt-in, we shouldn't catch import errors but fail
instead. Missing dependencies should prevent the use of the library.

Closes-bug: #1338485
Change-Id: Icd53d2928ec9571f3141006262a0da163c6857b0

In order to handle the deprecated notifier_strategy configuration option
we just need to translate the notifier_strategy value as follows:

  default -> transport_url=None, driver='noop'
  noop -> transport_url=None, driver='noop'
  logging -> transport_url=None, driver='log'
  rabbit -> transport_url=rabbit:///, driver='messaging'
  qpid -> transport_url=qpid:///, driver='messaging'
  None -> transport_url=None, driver=None

where the last bit simply means that the user hasn't specified any
notifier_strategy and we should just have oslo.messaging load a notifier
based on oslo.messaging's config options.

It really doesn't need to be any more complicated than that, and we
certainly shouldn't need to poke at what the user may have configured
for transport_url in their config file.

The reason this is important is that CONF.transport_url is a private
configuration option which soon will not be visible to users of the
oslo.messaging API. See I9c3bf74f13a820ce295aa77a2bbcd781778b5926.

       self.assertEqual(str(nfier._transport._driver._url),

Naughty, naughty!

since we deprecated it in Icehouse, but this patch will be useful to
backport to stable/icehouse in any case.

want to run Icehouse glance with Juno oslo.messaging ... say during an

commit_message:
notifier: simply notifier_strategy compat support

In order to handle the deprecated notifier_strategy configuration option
we just need to translate the notifier_strategy value as follows:

  default -> transport_url=None, driver='noop'
  noop -> transport_url=None, driver='noop'
  logging -> transport_url=None, driver='log'
  rabbit -> transport_url=rabbit:///, driver='messaging'
  qpid -> transport_url=qpid:///, driver='messaging'
  None -> transport_url=None, driver=None

where the last bit simply means that the user hasn't specified any
notifier_strategy and we should just have oslo.messaging load a notifier
based on oslo.messaging's config options.

It really doesn't need to be any more complicated than that, and we
certainly shouldn't need to poke at what the user may have configured
for transport_url in their config file.

The reason this is important is that CONF.transport_url is a private
configuration option which soon will not be visible to users of the
oslo.messaging API. See I9c3bf74f13a820ce295aa77a2bbcd781778b5926.

Also, simplify the testing of this stuff by mocking the oslo.messaging
APIs used and using the test scenarios outlined above. This also means
we stop poking around in oslo.messaging internals like:

       self.assertEqual(str(nfier._transport._driver._url),
                        'qpid:///')

Naughty, naughty!

Note: it's arguable we should just remove notifier_strategy in Juno
since we deprecated it in Icehouse, but this patch will be useful to
backport to stable/icehouse in any case.

BACKPORT NOTE (markmc): The idea with backporting it is that you might
want to run Icehouse glance with Juno oslo.messaging ... say during an
upgrade ... and Juno oslo.messaging will likely enforce this as a
private implementation detail, thereby breaking Icehouse glance.

Change-Id: I067248974baee50a2a0afb38bf022b65d1bea57a
(cherry picked from commit 4d6e55f40ce88414480df01b1f59ba1ed758e7d4)

@harry

The typo is corrected.

When working on the 2 similar code blocks, we did consider whether some common part could be abstracted. But we noticed that if we wanted to use something like decorator, the interface of the decorator might be too complicated to address the minor differences. And the 2 blocks look similar now just because they happen to react to the same error similarly. But in future, more differences may show up. So our proposal is that we keep the code in current state and observe the code evolution to get a better idea to take the common part out later. commit_message:
Address 0x712d8e0e error in VNX Cinder Driver

In original implementation, 0x712d8e0e error is not considered.
Thus, some snapshot creation and volume extending operations may fail
when the system is in a transition state.

This patch is to add some waiting and retry logic when 0x712d8e0e error
comes out so that the system is more error-tolerant.

Change-Id: I615e49693ada7cf25fd2d2fa224f76c6f20cf630
Closes-Bug: #1443338

commit_message:
Fix a bug about cluster status

Cluster status will be set to DELETING when ClusterAction.do_delete
is invokded. After nodes deletion finished, cluster status should
be set to DELETED by invoking do_delete method of Cluster module.
But current implementation in Cluster.do_delete is incorrect. This
pacth fixed this issue.

Change-Id: Ie6e1956f7854de4747dd569b886591d48b86be56

commit_message:
Use the proper parameter to set --master

The interface for pcmk_resource offers the parameter master_params to set
--master during the resource creation.

Change-Id: I6fa769f14a6248b371810af3ba6819a1f9ed9442

commit_message:
Add Observer Service and RPC Methods for it

Added a new Service named Heat Observer. It hosts a RPC Service
with the topic Observer. RPC API calls also added to allow simple
DB operations.

Change-Id: If10313d548e22b55104b802b656ba5221c0b0f78

[{'created': '2015-05-27 18:06:29.000000000', 'message': 'Do not assume order of dictionary elements in init_l3

This fixes the test_interface unit tests[1] that breaks with a
randomized PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that the init_l3 method from
neutron.agent.linux.interface had dictionary elements in a particular
order. Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=2.

The fix refactors the test case to handle unsorted dictionaries in
init_l3.

[1] neutron.tests.unit.agent.linux.test_interface.TestABCDriver

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: I1948593b4d7a0069ef060512942b548c74a6b369
'}]
commit_message:
Do not assume order of dictionary elements in init_l3

This fixes the test_interface unit tests[1] that breaks with a
randomized PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that the init_l3 method from
neutron.agent.linux.interface had dictionary elements in a particular
order. Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=2.

The fix refactors the test case to handle unsorted dictionaries in
init_l3.

[1] neutron.tests.unit.agent.linux.test_interface.TestABCDriver

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: I1948593b4d7a0069ef060512942b548c74a6b369

commit_message:
Do not assume order of get_sync_data_metering response elements

This fixes the test_add_metering_label_rpc_call[1] unit tests that breaks
with a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that the get_sync_data_metering[2] had response
elements in a particular order. Found with PYTHONHASHSEED=1.

The fix refactors the test_add_metering_label_rpc_call test case to handle
an unsorted get_sync_data_metering response. The fix defines the class
UnorderedList[3] which is equal to any permutation of itself.

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

[1] neutron.tests.unit.services.metering.test_metering_plugin:
 TestMeteringPluginL3AgentScheduler
 TestMeteringPluginL3AgentSchedulerServicePlugin
[2] neutron.services.metering.metering_plugin.MeteringPlugin
[3] neutron.tests.tools

Change-Id: I5d42b827bc72dcacd38eaa2377ce16c47a9e7dbb

commit_message:
Backported some bootstrap processes for gating

This change backports the ansible install process from master when
using the `bootstrap-ansible.sh` script. This was backported
because the pip install process for ansible version 1.6.10 no longer
works due to upstream changes in the location of the ansible core
modules.

This also adds logging to the gate run and cleans up the console
output so that we can better understand what is going on.

This change should resolve the issues where the ansible core modules
are returning an error stating the following:
 "is not a legal parameter in an Ansible task or handler"

Change-Id: I03160f8159b465f9cb1381312cdc65e572fb2dbd

Regarding http://paste.openstack.org/show/154798/

1. you need to initialize the list in one place as part of setup. You'll get more accurate results that way.

2. You run the test using dict() more times than you run it using a dictionary comprehension. Probably for the following reason

3. The difference between the first two results is half a *micro*second.

    1000000 loops, best of 5: 1.14 usec per loop
    1000000 loops, best of 5: 1.69 usec per loop

Granted, this can have worse performance, but you show only one run when the results suite you. You should run the dictionary comprehension timeit several times as well, with proper setup. The results are closer than you are trying to demonstrate here."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-28 17:02:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

"}, {'created': '2015-01-28 03:57:01.000000000', 'message': "Performance:leverage dict comprehension in PEP-0274

PEP-0274 introduced dict comprehensions to replace dict constructor
with a sequence of key-pairs[1], these are benefits:
  The dictionary constructor approach has two distinct disadvantages
  from the proposed syntax though.  First, it isn't as legible as a
  dict comprehension.  Second, it forces the programmer to create an
  in-core list object first, which could be expensive.

Glance dropped python 2.6 support in Kilo, we can leverage this now.
There is deep dive about PEP-0274[2] and basic tests about
performance[3].
Note: This commit doesn't handle dict constructor with kwargs.
This commit also adds a hacking rule.

[1]http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0274/
[2]http://doughellmann.com/2012/11/12/the-performance-impact-of-using-dict-instead-of-in-cpython-2-7-2.html
[3]http://paste.openstack.org/show/154798/

Change-Id: I0ba408f9c616dcdb09618f6256db76b9facc0c1d
"}, {'created': '2015-01-28 04:21:31.000000000', 'message': "Performance:leverage dict comprehension in PEP-0274

PEP-0274 introduced dict comprehensions to replace dict constructor
with a sequence of key-pairs[1], these are benefits:
  The dictionary constructor approach has two distinct disadvantages
  from the proposed syntax though.  First, it isn't as legible as a
  dict comprehension.  Second, it forces the programmer to create an
  in-core list object first, which could be expensive.

Glance dropped python 2.6 support in Kilo, we can leverage this now.
There is deep dive about PEP-0274[2] and basic tests about
performance[3].

commit_message:
Leverage dict comprehension in PEP-0274

PEP-0274 introduced dict comprehensions to replace dict constructor
with a sequence of key-pairs[1], these are two benefits:
- First, it makes the code look neater.
- Second, it gains a micro-optimization.

Glance dropped python 2.6 support in Kilo, we can leverage this now.
Note: This commit doesn't handle dict constructor with kwargs.
This commit also adds a hacking rule.

[1]http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0274/

Co-Authored-By: ChangBo Guo(gcb) <eric.guo@easystack.cn>
Co-Authored-By: Kamil Rykowski <kamil.rykowski@intel.com>
Change-Id: I0ba408f9c616dcdb09618f6256db76b9facc0c1d

commit_message:
Fix deprecated_group of rpc_conn_pool_size

When rpc_conn_pool_size have been moved from amqp.py to base.py:

  87137e7af05f12a99bd04566036fbf71824f45cf

We loose the deprecated_group, this change reintroduces it.

commit_message:
Fix: iSCSI iqn name RFC violation

Pior to this patch the name generated by Ironic for the iSCSI target was
violating the RFC 3720 and RFC 3721, and this was messing up with some
tools consuming it (see deploy-targetcli element for diskimage-builder).

This patch fixing this generating a name that complies to the RFCs.

commit_message:
Add alarm for rabbitmq_max_channels_per_conn

This commit adds a new alarm for metric rabbitmq_max_channels_per_conn,
which is a metric representing the largest (max) number of channels per
connection across all rabbitmq connections. We have chosen a threshold
of 10 -- running a dev cluster periodically sees
rabbitmq_max_channels_per_conn > 1 and 10 is an 'arbitrary but likely
reasonable limit' which we can use to prevent channel ballooning.

Change-Id: I40bd5dde25d61e2febb8699dbcd1e28b0f25674c
Closes-Bug: #1459249

commit_message:
compute utils: Remove a useless context parameter

get_device_name_for_instance used to require a context to be passed in
explicitly, but this is no longer required, so this patch removes it
from the signature.

commit_message:
Add second monitor operation to check RabbitMQ

This commit checks whether there is a running
cluster of rabbitmq and if rabbitmq app is running
on the node and exits with non-zero code if
current node is not running rabbitmq, but should
do so

Change-Id: I2098405b39ade7325b94781aeb997de0937bdf4c
Closes-bug: #1458828

commit_message:
Remove direct DB calls from glusterfs_native driver

- Remove direct DB calls from methods create_snapshot() and
delete_snapshot().
- Move code from _update_gluster_vols_dict() method to
ensure_share() method.

Note that the original of this change was submitted as
a fix to #1444914; however, we've backported it to
Kilo for the purpose of fixing an other bug, as indicated
below.

Change-Id: I6c95f6d9361093d832a536971a460c3cdda44dcb
Closes-Bug: #1447692
(cherry picked from commit 4eb57f53c1c705fa3abf2ab0c2973fe709dbe6c8)

IMO, this change is probably unnecessary. When you mention a version it means it's supported in all later versions, unless deprecated."}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-05-25 08:11:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

From you description, 'version' and 'since' are the same parameter in support status. Is it better to just change param 'version' to 'since'?"}, {'account_id': 13009, 'date': '2015-05-25 09:38:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hmm... Nope, since is necessary and there is differency between version and since. Since means that from which release objects is available and version is from which release current status. For example, RouterGateway:
SupportStatus(since: '2013.1', status: support.DEPRECATED, version: '2014.1') means RouterGateway available since 2013.1 and DEPRECATED since 2014.1. This parameter allows to watch all life cycle of object."}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2015-05-25 19:13:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Peter, I might be bike-shedding, but for me the semantics of those words is actually vice versa (if we are bound only to "version" and "since") - "version" is since when a resource has appeared at all, and "since" is the version since it has the currently assigned "status", as in "has support status STATUS since ..".'}, {'account_id': 13009, 'date': '2015-05-28 09:47:37.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Due to IRC meeting with Steve Baker.'}, {'account_id': 13009, 'date': '2015-05-28 10:04:35.000000000', 'content': 'Restored'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 10:04:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Add since parameter to SupportStatus

since which release object is available. Also, add
this parameter to resources/properties where it neeeded.

partial bp deprecating-improvements

commit_message:
Backported some bootstrap processes for gating

This change backports the ansible install process from master when
using the `bootstrap-ansible.sh` script. This was backported
because the pip install process for ansible version 1.6.10 no longer
works due to upstream changes in the location of the ansible core
modules.

This also adds logging to the gate run and cleans up the console
output so that we can better understand what is going on.

This change should resolve the issues where the ansible core modules
are returning an error stating the following:
 "is not a legal parameter in an Ansible task or handler"

Change-Id: I03160f8159b465f9cb1381312cdc65e572fb2dbd

commit_message:
Leave wiggle room for zake and kazoo fix releases

While talking through change Ib6f79cfcd18a758ce4b2a86f3ff323d533db4640
and force merging it, it was noted that we should leave some room in
global-requirements for zake and kazoo to put out fix releases of their
own so we don't end up wedging the gate again and requiring another
force merge on one of those projects.

Related-Bug: #1459322

Change-Id: I0905c5e02f00ea7a20be606a1f32b61f8379ac88

commit_message:
VMware: Fix base exceptions changed in oslo.vmware 0.13.0

Latest oslo.vmware 0.13.0 throws a VimFaultException instead of a
VMwareDriverException when an unknown fault is raised in the suds
layer. The patch fixes the unit tests and one other place in the
code to catch the right exception.

Note: the code is backward compatible and we will still support
the vexc.VMwareDriverException exception if an older oslo.vmware
version is used. This will be deprecated in Nova the next cycle.

Closes-Bug: #1459021

Change-Id: I32de592e6fbb9036cfcb02865da0416b3d2ee170

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-26 08:25:09.000000000', 'message': 'Do lazy start attempts of the rabbit app

W/o this patch, the rabbitmq app may remain joined cluster
but not started and keep running without being noticed by
OCF logic. But by design, the app is supposed to be stopped for
some cases and monitor action should not treat this state
as en error.

This is a problem as we don't want permanent states with
the rabbit app retained stopped because in this state the
rabbit node cannot process AMQP at all. Besides that,
we also want the rabbit app to be ready ASAP, but w/o some
"lazy start" attempts, the unavailability window only increases.

The solution is to make the rabbit app at least have tried
to start (a lazy start attempt) in the end of monitor
and post-promote and ignore results because it is normal
when it cannot start for some transient cluster states.
And at the post-start, also check if the rabbit app can be
started and report the resource as not running, if it cannot.
This will ensure eventual readiness of the rabbitmq app in the
stop-start loop along with minimizing its downtime.

Closes-bug: #1455761

Change-Id: Iffdb53860a4b53b0f7b6b1798aeb8088e7bc542c
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Do lazy start attempts of the rabbit app

W/o this patch, the rabbitmq app may remain joined cluster
but not started and keep running without being noticed by
OCF logic. But by design, the app is supposed to be stopped for
some cases and, in general, the monitor action should not
treat this state as en error.

This is a problem as we don't want the rabbit app retained
stopped because in this state the rabbit node cannot process
AMQP at all.

The solution is to make the rabbit app at least have tried
to start (a lazy start attempt) in the end of monitor
and ignore results because it is normal when the app cannot start
for some transient cluster states.

Closes-bug: #1458828

Change-Id: Iffdb53860a4b53b0f7b6b1798aeb8088e7bc542c
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

I also feel it not necessary to revert it. Making vmware driver correctly handle the exception should be fine.'}, {'account_id': 9171, 'date': '2015-05-27 09:35:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think the original commit is doing the right thing and fixing this in nova seems to be right approach.'}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2015-05-27 13:35:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

We shouldn't encourage libraries to release backwards-incompatible changes without warning by absorbing the impact"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-05-27 13:41:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

You guys are failing to consider that nova is not the only consumer of the oslo.vmware library, which was returning exception type A before and is now returning exception type B - that's a backwards incompatible change w/o any deprecation cycle for clients to adjust to changes in the library.  It's immaterial that we just know about the nova vmware driver having problems here."}, {'account_id': 9171, 'date': '2015-05-27 15:07:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

wait_for_task was meant to raise exceptions which are sub-classes of VimException, which correspond to errors while calling vSphere APIs. It is clearly documented here:
https://github.com/openstack/oslo.vmware/blob/master/oslo_vmware/api.py#L375

I don't remember which changeset has introduced the behavior to throw VMwareDriverException instead. 

The contract set by the API doc is clearly followed in the case of VMware Cinder driver."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-05-27 16:48:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

We need to find a way to clean up the exceptions without breaking backwards compatibility. If we want callers of functions to only catch certain exceptions, we should declare that clearly in the documentation.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-05-27 17:10:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

yeah, I think reverting this and sorting out some exception hierarchy and better docs is the right approach.

I think we need a way to make this bug fix and not cause existing users to break, it should be possible I think.'}, {'account_id': 8574, 'date': '2015-05-28 05:46:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Exactly speaking, Vim session should raise VimFaultException, rather than VMwareDriverException. That means the current code in https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/virt/vmwareapi/vm_util.py#L1281 is incorrect. Perhaps that mistake is not discovered during vmware driver code refactor, and exists for a long time.'}, {'account_id': 8574, 'date': '2015-05-28 05:54:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I feel we may not totally regard it as a backward capability problem. Assuming that we implement one api call in a wrong way, which returns a wrong type of data. We will definitely need to fix the wrong code. Maybe we have to continue to have the wrong code for a little time, in order to keep backward compatibility. However, we do need to remove it eventually.

Now our problem is that compatibility test is neither done by Nova, nor oslo.vmware. Nova always consumes the latest code of oslo.vmware. If anyone merges wrong code in oslo.vmware, which breaks the compatibility, Nova unit test might be broken.

Usually the compatibility test is done by code consumer, if Nova limits oslo.vmware version number to ensure compatibility, the compatibility test can be covered by Nova CI jobs when we adjust its version number. However, it makes inconvienence to consume new oslo.vmware code.'}, {'account_id': 8574, 'date': '2015-05-28 07:06:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

remove -1'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-05-28 08:15:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-05-28 08:32:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1

Sorry for the balagan. Lets revert in the mean time and clean up nova so that it will no longer make use of invalid or incorrect exceptions.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-28 08:32:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Revert "Raise VimFaultException for unknown faults"

This reverts commit 1668fef9cabea6a23023aab6b97617b4368b14d6

This is a backwards incompatible change, as we see with the
nova driver code that is expecting a VMwareDriverException
but is now getting back a VimFaultException because the unit
tests in nova were passing an unknown fault class name.

Change-Id: I0f8042c6e47f6eb9802e770ffb7d09bdbe57013b
Closes-Bug: #1459021

commit_message:
Port test_inspector to Python 3

* Replace contextlib.nested() with contextlib.ExitStack
* Add contextlib2 dependency for Python 2.6 and 2.7 to get ExitStack
* TestLibvirtInspection: set libvirtError because it must be a subclass
  of Exception on Python 3

Enable ceilometer.tests.compute.virt.libvirt.test_inspector on Python 3.

Change-Id: I82f4b911c1b3ede90805150630c222b1dd5f3474

commit_message:
Fix usage of dictionary methods on Python 3

Convert the result of keys(), values() and items() dict method to list
when a list is expected. On Python 3, these methods now return an
iterator, not a list.

Instead of getting the key with .keys()[0] and then the value with
.values()[0], get both at the same time using .items()[0]. It ensures
that the key is consistent with the value, but it is also more
efficient.

Enable ceilometer.tests.storage.test_impl_sqlalchemy on Python 3.4.

Change-Id: I4bcd3dfbca3e26238cdcdf19801244497dac2729

[{'created': '2015-05-19 20:20:48.000000000', 'message': "Check for encrypted_param_names key in environment

If unencrypted data exists in the database, there will be no
'encrypted_param_names' key in the environment.  Check for this key
before referencing it.

Change-Id: Ie8c593818a64d150e815487e1449a52173f1ab5d
Closes-Bug: #1456700
"}]
commit_message:
Check for encrypted_param_names key in environment

If unencrypted data exists in the database, there will be no
'encrypted_param_names' key in the environment.  Check for this key
before referencing it.

Change-Id: Ie8c593818a64d150e815487e1449a52173f1ab5d
Closes-Bug: #1456700

commit_message:
Log instance console when ssh fails in EC2 test

To aid in debugging gate failures, this change adds logging of the
instance console when ssh to the instance fails. This is already
being done in the tempest/scenario/manager.py

Change-Id: I34a792378350f52081b6857084521fdd60ede6c2

Telemetry service comes with high overhead by consuming higher
resources than expected for the default minimal cluster configuration
for training labs.

Commented out the telementry related scripts under the config folder.

Change-Id: I6d53c4aefe689100c0315a366430a34ff1a807fe
'}]
commit_message:
labs: Disable telemetry service

Telemetry service comes with high overhead by consuming higher
resources than expected for the default minimal cluster configuration
for training labs.

Commented out the telementry related scripts under the config folder.
To re-enable it, just uncomment the required lines.

Change-Id: I6d53c4aefe689100c0315a366430a34ff1a807fe

[{'created': '2015-05-26 09:23:57.000000000', 'message': 'Fixing event types pattern for Role Noti. handler

Identity(Keystone) notifications have a handler
for Role that has event type as identity.role.*
Another for RoleAssignment which accepts
identity.role_assignment.* events.

Since event types are regular expressions,
an event like identity.role_assignment.created
is matched with identity.role.* and gets incorrectly
routed to the Role Handler.

This fix restricts the event type regex for Role
handler to just identity.role.* events and excludes
identity.role_* events.

Change-Id: I526467ef2f8204e8093f7470b86949e3e0e69990
Closes-Bug: #1457785
(cherry picked from commit 02bab799bab051cc22f4fdf9d19d7a17939cdde7)
'}]
commit_message:
Fixing event types pattern for Role Noti. handler

Identity(Keystone) notifications have a handler
for Role that has event type as identity.role.*
Another for RoleAssignment which accepts
identity.role_assignment.* events.

Since event types are regular expressions,
an event like identity.role_assignment.created
is matched with identity.role.* and gets incorrectly
routed to the Role Handler.

This fix restricts the event type regex for Role
handler to just identity.role.* events and excludes
identity.role_* events.

Change-Id: I526467ef2f8204e8093f7470b86949e3e0e69990
Closes-Bug: #1457785
(cherry picked from commit 02bab799bab051cc22f4fdf9d19d7a17939cdde7)

Spec for adding Barbican service as Keystone credential backend.

Clarified project scope token requirement and related changes in
driver API. Added limitation details when Barbican is used as
backend.

commit_message:
Refactor ilo.common._prepare_floppy_image()

This patch refactors the code related to tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile()
and try/finally block in ilo.common._prepare_floppy_image() for
readability and succinctness based on the comment made in iRMC
Virtual Media Deploy module review process.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/151958/19/ironic/drivers/modules/irmc/deploy.py

Change-Id: I18b8a49503b665c8ef73b438fa2ced9d8d97fa25

commit_message:
Use lua locks instead of pipeline locks

Lua locks are less prone to retries (and client side
flapping) so instead of using pipelines and retries on
those pipelines just use the simpler (and guaranteed
server-side atomic) lua based locks instead.

Change-Id: I3a03e040b56fd9ac97b7e5d00463ec961c81084a

commit_message:
Allow integer logging levels

Integer's are valid level names, and for some libraries
they have a lower level than DEBUG that is typically defined
at level 5, so to make that accessible, try to convert the
level name to a integer, and if not keep the original...

Change-Id: I5e7593735112d3e623231c428f680d53a52776a9

commit_message:
Mock url_available and ntp_available functions

With the addition of the url_available and ntp_available puppet
functions as part of the connectivity tests, we need to mock them out
for our noop tests so we don't actually fail when an test url is used.

Change-Id: I578e266e931f12d2e620a80994257871181e9f9b
Partial-Bug: 1261940
Closes-Bug: 1455702

commit_message:
Remove oslo.utils dependency

Remove oslo.utils as it has additional dependencies. We still need to
rely on iso8601 which oslo.utils was using.

Change-Id: Ic7da1e7c39e0e7bfa3470c50ef1f3b6df81ac021

commit_message:
Added CORS wildcard handling

The CORS specification permits the declaration of '*' as a response
wildcard domain, which explicitly allows _all_ domains to break
the single-origin policy. While we DO NOT recommend this method,
the ability to set a global policy should be included for the
sake of completeness.

Change-Id: Ifcc65ca74fa976dbd322a7ffd4ffba5443d1df5b

Administrative abandon of the spec. This spec is being abandoned as it is still targeted to the Kilo release. Any core or the original owner can reinstate the change. If the spec is reinstated, it should be retargeted to either the current release or the backlog.

As a secondary note, I don't see a huge win adding another token backend that requires persistence. The long term goal is to move away from the need to persist tokens in any backend."}]

**disclaimer** Yes, I did open and read the presentation pasted on the bottom of the specification.

I have some questions:

1) (sorry if I am repeating that). In the presentation, when you say 'IdP 1 isues attribute >>a<<' do you mean the parameter, say E_MAIL_ADDRESS or its value e.g marek.denis@cern.notexists ? 

2) Do you think your proposal will also work for a use-case where a public cloud provider wants to sell some of the resources to multiple smaller clouds, and those clouds should not have shared resources accessible? I'd say the public cloud is within multiple (tiny) federations. I would also say I want to have a different mappings for every single IdP. Simply because I want to map federated users into different set of groups (hence roles). I don't want Pepsi guys to access projects owned by Cola guys.

Also, while I see the problem on slide no 5, I think on slide 6, since all the rules are equal you can create the mapping rule once and later use it many times.

Maybe we should combine it all and let administrator to combine multiple rules, so when adding a protocol one could specify a list of rules that are going to be used?"}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2014-06-17 17:41:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

Answered your main issue Steve, will upload a new patch soon.'}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2014-06-18 10:49:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Marek, in answer to your questions:

1. The attribute is the combination of both type and value, so we could trust IDP1 to issue E_MAIL_ADDRESS=marek.denis@cern.notexists, or just to issue E_MAIL_ADDRESS with any value.

2. I think there are a few ways in which this could be accomplished:
  a) Allowing the IDP to be used as an external attribute for mapping.
  b) Have IDP specific mappings (as in current system)
  c) If each IdP has an attribute which is issued uniquely by this IdP then this can be used in the mapping rules

I think I would prefer a).

What do you think?'}, {'account_id': 5956, 'date': '2014-06-18 12:44:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-18 12:44:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

So, this seems to be like you are removing the association between mapping and idp (removing it at the protocol level), and just re-introducing it (optionally) at the mapping layer via 'only_applies_to_idps'.

700+ lines later, what I got from this is: add 'only_applies_to_idps', because if we have N idps that share *some* attributes, we want 1 really large map instead of N smaller maps.

Which I guess is fine, I can see arguments for both ways, depends on how the administrator does things. But can you please trim this down? It took way too long to get to the point."}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2014-07-09 22:08:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-09 22:08:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: -Verified

(6 comments)

(discussed at the keystone juno hackathon)

This produces a bigger and more complicated mapping than those we have today (contradicting the title), and more importantly, seems to introduce a backwards incompatibility with the existing IdP-mapping relationship.

When you have all IdP's using the same mapping, you also introduce the risk of breaking **all** IdP's when changing the mapping for **one** IdP."}, {'account_id': 10335, 'date': '2014-11-21 11:17:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

The proposed mapping is definitely an improvement in order to create a cloud service for a national research federation having hundreds of IdPs. Research organisations have this problem now.

Remove the relation one-to-one between IdP and mapping is very good.

Nevertheless, several part of the spec are not clear or need extra information. Some comment on-line.'}, {'account_id': 10335, 'date': '2014-11-21 11:18:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: -Code-Review

Do you plan to move this in Kilo?'}, {'account_id': 6534, 'date': '2014-11-21 11:28:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

There was too much resistance to this change to get it into Juno. We have no plans at the moment to push for this spec again in Kilo. However, if and when mapping rules are re-evaluated (which they will be) we will push for the  revised spec to make the rules independent of the IDP, in order to cater for large federations such as academic community ones.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-02-06 05:00:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16: Code-Review-2'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-05-28 08:44:30.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Administrative abandonment of this change. This change is targeted to juno. This spec can be reinstated by any core and/or the original owner. If the spec is reinstated, please retarget to the current release or the backlog.'}]

commit_message:
Simplified Mapping for Federated Authentication

It is proposed that the mapping API for mapping external federated
attributes to internal groups and users should be simplified to be
independent of the identity provider. In addition, the return values
of protocol handling modules should be standardized.

Change-Id: Ifbdebe5a7ccb258d2fc862ed51af3ded55c69153
Co-Authored-By: David Chadwick <d.w.chadwick@kent.ac.uk>

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-16 15:44:55.000000000', 'message': 'Trusted Attributes Policy for External Identity Providers

Proposes a feature to add fine grained control over which attributes (both
types and values) Keystone will accept as trustworthy from an external identity

commit_message:
Trusted Attributes Policy for External Identity Providers

Proposes a feature to add fine grained control over which
attributes (both types and values) Keystone will accept as
trustworthy from an external identity provider. All attributes
(types and/or values) that are not trusted should be
discarded by federated Keystone.

Change-Id: I846f5567b6d97bc9eb3d430950440e41ece6fb79
Co-Authored-By: David Chadwick <d.w.chadwick@kent.ac.uk>

commit_message:
Remove unused context parameter

Below methods from volume utils are not using context parameter:
1. _usage_from_volume
2. _usage_from_backup
3. _usage_from_snapshot
4. _usage_from_consistencygroup
5. _usage_from_cgsnapshot

So the context parameter is removed from all of these methods.

Closes-Bug: #1454212
Change-Id: Id87c5635db4a0e8df00f7bd7b87ffe60876f255c

commit_message:
Skip decrypt parameters when get from db object

If there is no 'encrypted_param_names'  in
raw_template.environment set default value []
for them to avoid raising KeyError.

Change-Id: I71a23499152ca4cd3c530fdcb3162c43b9e3b8b5
Closes-Bug: #1459498

commit_message:
Relese notes for zaqarclient 0.1.1

6707d41 Drop incubating theme from docs
24aeae5 Deleted unuseful line
f81c36d Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package
0047c54 Fix handling of 1.1 API
2bd784e Gets 'flavor' data if the resource exists
f5f35d4 Gets 'pool' data if the resource exists
ff13b7a Handling exception on 504 Error
e4af424 Updated from global requirements
99f0b35 Added i18n support
2cb7e90 Makes health return True or False
19ec61d Remove unused openstack/common modules
369ac1e Adds encapsulation control to the client
f96c739 Updated from global requirements
4d957e6 Extend some docstrings with useful information
632c893 Add reference docs for latest recommended client
be666ff Add docs for `Client` instances
d8a5061 Setup developer docs for zaqarclient
a411bf0 Fix the client name typo
4e60be5 Updated from global requirements
ad673c5 fix KeystoneAuth doc string
0c6c0d7 Updated from global requirements
d721b75 Updates API name
ebb8d56 Add a read-only property for Queues

Change-Id: I38d88788a3753da888211055de91e3aa1a9d7bbb

messages:
[{'account_id': 11650, 'date': '2015-05-26 10:52:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 11650, 'date': '2015-05-26 10:58:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Change has come out wrong... and doesn't correspond to the heat-coe-patch"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-26 11:15:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-magnum-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/60/185560/1/check/gate-magnum-pep8/dbdb7d6/ : SUCCESS in 2m 02s

(1 comment)

This will break the manually scaling feature. I think we need two templates: one for manual scaling; the other for auto scaling.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-26 14:05:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-magnum-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/60/185560/3/check/gate-magnum-pep8/be5913f/ : SUCCESS in 1m 33s
- gate-magnum-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/60/185560/3/check/gate-magnum-docs/fa702ca//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 44s
- gate-magnum-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/60/185560/3/check/gate-magnum-python27/67e7655/ : SUCCESS in 1m 57s
- check-functional-dsvm-magnum http://logs.openstack.org/60/185560/3/check/check-functional-dsvm-magnum/e4920a5/ : SUCCESS in 47m 03s (non-voting)
- gate-magnum-tox-bandit http://logs.openstack.org/60/185560/3/check/gate-magnum-tox-bandit/e09d1ab/ : SUCCESS in 1m 39s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 668, 'date': '2015-05-26 14:42:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

The AutoScalingGroup allows for a webhook to manually trigger the scale up and scale down events. We can wire the back-end of "magnum bay-update replace node_count=N" with a call to the appropriate webhook. This way we can have both automatic and manual scaling of bays.

The triggering of a bay scale event in the most common case will be when the sum of all -m (memory limit) arguments exceeds a configurable threshold of all memory in the bay. When true, add enough nodes to the bay to bring it under the threshold again. Make the threshold a configuration directive in the magnum configuration file, and provide a way for an operator to change the value while the server is running without a restart.

Some exceptions to consider:

1) If the -m argument of the current request is larger than the size of the node in our scaling group, then fail the request without scaling out, as no number of new nodes will accommodate such a request.

2) Be sure to implement time dampening. If it takes a few minutes to add a bay node, and I try several times to launch a container that I don't have room for, don't add extra nodes.

3) Not all container creations will happen through the Magnum API. Some may happen on the bay directly using the COE. For this reason we must periodically poll the COE and decide if a scaling action is appropriate based on the current utilization of the bay.'}, {'account_id': 11650, 'date': '2015-05-26 16:53:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I will abandon this patch and rebase around it. Further autoscaling work will come from other patches.'}, {'account_id': 11536, 'date': '2015-05-26 17:47:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

@Adrian, thanks for your remarks. Yes, I believe the manually scaling can be fixed in the way you suggested. I revoked my vote for that. Just two concerns:

1. Is that a way to disable autosacling. I believe some operators just want a static bay. I think we need to figure out a way to disable the autoscaling to adopt this use case.

2. How to enable users to implement an external autoscaler. I believe some operators won't be satisfied for the default autoscaler provided by COE. We need to enable them to plug a custom autoscaler.

Both #1 and #2 is unlikely to happen if we used a single template for both manually scaling and auto scaling."}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-05-28 05:06:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I do not like scale down until there is infraastructure to deal with it in kubernetes and swarm (and in the future mesos).

Regards
-steve'}, {'account_id': 11650, 'date': '2015-05-28 08:02:59.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

The coe's cannot deal with downscaling, further work needed to add autoscaling correctly."}]

Raise HTTPBadRequest instead of ValueError for API validation

Raise HTTPBadRequest exception instead of ValueError for
parameters validation.

Resource tracker: remove invalid conductor call from tests

Commit 2427d288bc017a5b91430ffe16419d47703d2060 removed the code
usning the conductor to update the instance. There was no need
to set the stubs for this.

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Resource tracker: use instance objects for claims

This partially makes the resource tracker use instance objects.

This is part of the blueprint make-resource-tracker-use-objects. The
compute manager passes an instance object to the claim.

Change-Id: I6e368586dbbb4da571cabc253eee9f4ac8f2b2ae

I'm not familiar with such hooks, and implementing them will probably not go well with the cores, since you're talking about a change that will deeply interact with practically everything in Neutron.

These tests should make sure that the code does what it should. For example the opencontrail plugin failed on this exactly since it didn't use the same delete_subnet function that is present in db_base_plugin_v2.py. Adding a new plugin will require tests and the tests will likely inherit from the base DB tests in which I'm implementing the tests for this code, so I'm fairly comfortable will letting future plugin-writers to see what they're missing on their own."}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2015-05-04 17:25:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 12444, 'date': '2015-05-04 17:27:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Add callback prior to deleting a subnet

When using LBaaS and trying to delete a subnet, neutron has no way of
knowing if the subnet is associated to some pool. As a result, the
subnet is deleted but the pool remains associated to the (now
nonexistent) subnet_id.  This patch lays the ground-work for adding a
check in LBaaS' side to prevent such cases.

Related-Bug: #1413817
Change-Id: I3d5e231b67c72ffd919c92d65b57da56c63e053c

Add release notes for 0.6.0

This adds release notes for the following commits:

    $ git log --oneline --no-merges 0.5.0..HEAD
    9d5ceab Drop py26 support
    752f9ca Disable propagating BadStoreConfiguration
    78984a8 Sync up with global-requirements
    f33fe43 Handle optional dependency in vmware store

commit_message:
Block oslo.vmware 0.13.0 due to a backwards incompatible change

Lots of details on the global requirements patch that
this Depends-On.

Essentially, nova tests are broken with the oslo.vmware
release and we need to block this version.

Partial-Bug: #1459021

Depends-On: Icf1ce8dbb4b2c0b6b627d5d8be0b85a42e99c784
Change-Id: I4b9a471c9783dff769cbdec2e534bb0157f141f6

commit_message:
Use graduated version of oslo.policy

The detail of usage of oslo_policy is avaiable at
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.policy/usage.html
Now we need to pass oslo.config object to Enforcer.

All modules under openstack.common are only for
openstack.common.policy, so we can remove openstack/common safely.

Change-Id: I3e7bce0dcec4a16ab61d5cb4232a69bacfd0ccde

commit_message:
Pass wait_until arg in create_test_server call

wait_until argument is not passed when calling
create_test_server due to which it returns server details and then
test cleanup goes for deleting server which is still in build state
causing it to leave behind volume if server is booted using bootable
volume. passing wait_until arg fixes the issue. Also name variable
is getting ignored so adding condition to use name variable if passed.

Change-Id: I1fc92d4405226ac34058853df598be75bf921691
Closes-Bug: 1458295

commit_message:
Force order of dhcp.needs_resync_reasons dictionary elements

This fixes the test_periodoc_resync_helper unit test that breaks with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED (see the bug report).

The test assumed that the dhcp.needs_resync_reasons dictionary from
neutron.agent.dhcp.agent had elements in a particular order. Found with
PYTHONHASHSEED=2.

The fix refactors the test case to force a sorted dhcp.needs_resync_reasons
dictionary.

Partial-bug: #1348818

Note: There are several other unrelated unit tests that also break with
a randomized PYTHONHASHSEED, but they are not addressed here. They will
be addressed in separate patches.

Change-Id: Ia7fc2c3e605d92d8497d44e28054bdda613cebf2

commit_message:
Fixed grammatical errors in the V2 Client API doc

In the using-api-v2.rst document, various inconsistencies in spelling of
"openstackDemo", as well as the password under the "Creating Tenants" and
"Creating Users" sections.

Updated service names to adhere to the OpenStack service naming conventions.

Fixed capitalization of "Client" to "client".

Change-Id: Ib20782f5b05f7097158f606c6562f92126650b89
Closes-Bug: #1458015

commit_message:
Rename OS::Heat::StructuredDeployments

Rename the StructuredDeployments resource to StructuredDeploymentGroup
to avoid awkward situations when talking about the plural form of the
StructuredDeployment resource. This has been agreed at the Vancouver
summit.

The existing 'StructuredDeployments' resource is kept for backwards
compatibility, but with a deprecated status and corresponding
deprecation message.

Closes-Bug: #1458008

Change-Id: I5d274acf17f222c493d10ded50f87e05a075b424

commit_message:
Rename OS::Heat::SoftwareDeployments

Rename the SoftwareDeployments resource to SoftwareDeploymentGroup to
avoid awkward situations when talking about the plural form of the
SoftwareDeployment resource. This has been agreed at the Vancouver
summit.

The existing 'SoftwareDeployments' resource is kept for backwards
compatibility, but with a deprecated status and corresponding
deprecation message.

Change-Id: Iae38b4afcb924ba626eccadfd68712e708be2bff
Partial-Bug: #1458008

commit_message:
Disable ability to use certain bond modes in UI

This will hide 'broadcast', 'balance-xor', 'balance-alb', 'balance-tlb'
linux bond modes from UI in non-experimental mode.

Change-Id: Ie290bb4fdf880b4c8fbdcc72f2e08e9086dacf35
Related-Bug: #1458935

commit_message:
Increasing ring partition power

This document describes a process and
modifications to swift code that together
enable ring partition power to be increased
without cluster downtime.

Change-Id: I22a0e4c12dbfa38760fae58c60fa782e530e4f77

commit_message:
Brocade driver not parsing zone data correctly

There is an error in the parsing of zone information
in the Brocade zone manager driver. This patch ensures
the zone information is correctly parsed.

Closes-Bug: 1456996
Change-Id: I6477164af0a60997be295587e506b37d7e019bcf

commit_message:
Add port-security extension API test cases

Netron ml2 plugin introduces a new extension port-security from Kilo cycle,
this patch add the API test cases for it. It verifies the default value of the
attribute, for network and port. And It also verifies the confict between
setting port-security and sec-group/address-pairs.

Change-Id: Ie0ec090e8fdce7dbdbce14ef47f38e8e57f262d4
Partially Implements: blueprint ml2-ovs-portsecurity
Depends-On: I3035317c83d22804855517434bd8578719ce0436

commit_message:
Fix assertion examples

The "pure" SAML assertion example wasn't a valid assertion generated
by keystone and the ECP wrapped one was missing the two new attributes
"openstack_user_domain" and "openstack_project_domain".

Change-Id: Ib3cb926464c771bbf56f29f29145943b73e1ee63
Closes-Bug: 1459279

commit_message:
Run functional tests when no ceilometer endpoint

Currently if there is no metering endpoint in the service
catalog then no functional/integration tests can be done.

This change tolerates missing ceilometer endpoint.

Change-Id: I55d45048284c4e78b9a1a94a35ef3cddc7bc3a37

Fix sync local state periodic task for standalone mode

If Ironic runs as standalone service we should not use Keystone API.
This patch fixes periodic task for nodes take over.

Change-Id: Ied5a1967665b19877feef610607e5f0dbbd40ef9

commit_message:
Remove ServiceClient from share_client

ServiceClient will be removed soon and there is no reason to use
it. A client can directly be inherited from RestClient instead.

Change-Id: Ia400bcf08a271f1e596f33f72ee94e33d1f682ad
Partly-implements: bp tempest-plugin-interface

Is there a master list of remaining python3 issues anywhere? At the moment we are introducing more and more little changes into the code, including some really ugly six stuff, without any idea if we are even close to actually being able to work with python3.

To be honest, I think that I'd like to see a working python3 tree before we merge any more - we can then pull in the fixes in a clean manner, knowing the end-goal is possible.

Thoughts appreciated, otherwise I'm tempted to start hitting -2 on python3 stuff"}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-05-26 09:56:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

Victor replied on the mailing list. The short version is that there is one outstanding dependency which has the required patch(s) pending merge, and a subset of the unit tests can be made to work. It therefore looks like we can finally get python3 in Liberty timeframe. Therefore happy to change my vote.

commit_message:
Don't use dict.iterkeys()

Replace list(dict.iterkeys()) with list(dict). The call to iterkeys() is
useless and the iterkeys() method of dictionaries was removed in
Python 3

Change-Id: I16733643d4b92fe8134eec2549bbd679fe75fb9c

commit_message:
Replace "hardcode" in scenario tests

Replace "harcode" of device name for attached volume, like "vdb",
by option CONF.compute.volume_device_name in all scenario tests.

Change-Id: I1d390d95345367a8a29ac990429619fa044563a3
Closes-Bug: 1458649

commit_message:
Sort PO files to avoid random reorder

Changes like
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185848/1/horizon/locale/ca/LC_MESSAGES/djangojs.po
just reordered entries with no content change. Pass --sort-output to
msgattrib to filter the entries in alphabetical order so that any
rearrangements of the source files will not have an effect on the order
of the entries.

Change-Id: I2d9c91f3d1fbcf61ae21521758836793742389ed
